mall window of opportunity during the Occupation to legalize abortion, and afterwards, doctors and women battled religious groups to uphold the law. The pill, on the other hand, first appeared at an inauspicious moment in history. Until circumstances began to change in the mid-1980s, the pharmaceutical industry was the pill's lone champion: doctors, midwives, family planners, and women all opposed the pill as a potential threat to their livelihoods, abortion rights, and women's health.Clearly written and interwoven with often surprising facts about Japanese history and politics, Norgren's book fills vital gaps in the cross-national literature on the politics of reproduction, a subject that has received more attention in the European and American contexts. Abortion Before Birth Control will be a valuable resource for those interested in abortion and contraception policies, gender studies, modern Japanese history, political science, and public policy. This is a major contribution to the literature on reproductive rights and the role of civil society in a country usually discussed in the context of its industrial might.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAbortionzJapan. 0aAbortion. 0aBirth controlxGovernment policyzJapan. 0aConsumers' leagues. 0aContraception. 0aContraceptives. 0aFamily sizezJapan. 0aHistory. 0aHuman rights. 0aHumanities. 0aIndustries. 0aMedical care. 0aMedicinexHistory. 0aNon-governmental organizations. 0aObstetricsxSurgery. 0aOral contraceptives. 0aPeople with disabilities. 0aPersons. 0aPharmaceutical industry. 0aPolitical planning. 0aPolitics, Practical. 0aReproductive technology. 0aSocial control. 0aSocial sciences. 0aSociology. 0aSurgery, Operative. 0aTherapeutics. 0aWomenzJapanxSocial conditions. 0aWomen's rights. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan